 never go below 75% mana, holding it in reserve for bad pulls, other people's trains, or for a quick recharge of the cleric.  The 17 second cast time is actually ideal, as it means you can chain cast without <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>ever</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> taking aggro.  This leads to a nice, relaxed play style of chain nuking, punctuated with the occasional dropped rods.<br>
<br>
This is even more valuable on raid involving long fights.  You can drop rods, AND nuke, AND use your pet.  Does a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mage's</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> life get any sweeter than this?<br>
<br>
Any guild that uses their <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> on raids, to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Call of the Hero</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Summon Rod of Transvergence</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or to mass equip summoned focus items simply owes it to the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mage</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in question to acquire <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Boots of Bladecalling</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for them.  Possibly barring the epic, there is simply no other item I am aware of that has a greater effect on <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  A 250 mana nuke in 17 seconds is almost as good as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Flowing Thought 15</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> as far as casting <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock of Swords</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is concerned.<br>
<br>
A guild that is not willing to go out of their way to obtain <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Boots of Bladecalling</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for their hardworking <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a guild that simply uses their <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to equip other classes.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1422<br> <font color=#333333>(6/11/02 12:43:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthelibrary.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Raiders of the Lost Rod</span><hr size=1> Most of the considerations given previously regarding groups apply to raids, only more so.  In a raid, rods have three primary purposes.<br>
<br>
First, they reduce preparation and downtime, by charging up the mana of the buffing classes.  This also allows the raid to compensate for a shortage of a particular buffing class.<br>
<br>
Second, they allow the raid party to store up mana for use later in a long fight.  And yes, there are long fights.  Those that argue that rods are never necessary either enjoy a surplus of the appropriate classes and so can simply overpower their foes, are too timid to push the envelope of what their guild can do, or are simply ignorant.<br>
<br>
Third, they allow the raid party to transfer mana to whatever class needs the mana at the time.  While this is most often clerics, it can be other classes as well, such as enchanters or wizards.  This gives the raid much more flexibility, both with the mix of classes brought to the raid, and with the tactics employed.<br>
<br>
Prior to the start of the raid, I mem all the common focus items, wear them all, and approach each caster and priest.  I ask them what focus items they want, and give them those, and a rod.  I give every melee a rod.  While I could simply drop rods, this accomplishes several things.  First, it is NOT nearly as convenient to drop focus items, as unlike rods, they lack a distinctive appearance on the ground.  Second, it is an opportunity to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;shake hands,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> as it were, with everyone on the raid.  This lets me know who is on the raid. By rodding down to distribute summonies, I also train the healers to keep an eye on my health and keep me alive.  This <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>is</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> a social game, and I want people to know who I am, and what I am doing for them.  And that I notice them in return.  I am not <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Mage,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I have a name, and you'd better know it.  I refuse to be anybody's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;bitch,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> but will always help friends and allies.  Once the raid gets going, opening a trade window can be stupid or even fatal, and so dropping rods becomes appropriate.<br>
<br>
Thus everyone starts the raid with a rod and the necessary focus items.  If there is a junior Mage, and I think we might need it, I have them produce and distribute old-style <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Modulating Rods</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  If the fight will be long and tough, then the melee's rods can be dropped during the fight to extend the healing mana pool, and if not, they are still there just in case.<br>
<br>
Because the raid will likely be crowded, it is usually necessary to use the full inventory trick described earlier to drop rods easily.  Be careful if you have to loot something, and stack a few bandages to give you inventory space to hold it.<br>
<br>
From a stress point of view, you want to avoid the call of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Rods NOW!&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by desperate casters.  After the opening of the fight is done and the enemy is debuffed, it is best to drop an occasional rod inbetween other spells.  Move a little after dropping each rod, so it is clear how many are on the ground.  If you stand completely still while dropping multiple rods, it will look like there is only one on the ground, and casters that need it may be reluctant to take what appears to be the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;last&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> rod.  Leaving a little trail of rods makes it clear exactly how many are available.  Drop them near where the healers are, try to avoid making them come to you.<br>
<br>
If at all possible, group with a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shaman</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Torpor</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and in any case, insist on a healer in your group to watch your health bar.  As we have seen, regeneration buffs are the most efficient, barring <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Complete Heal</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, so <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Druids</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are just dandy for this purpose.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Love</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> your <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Druid</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, as they often feel unappreciated on raids <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (don't we all?)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  A group composed of mages, druids, and wizards is likely get to get experience for the kill as well, an added bonus.<br>
<br>
If you have a right click nuke, such as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Burnt Wood Staff</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Boots of Bladecalling</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> use them to conserve your mana.  You will find the long cast times on these also make it nearly impossible to gain aggro.<br>
<br>
If there is a crisis, and you must pump out a lot of rods in short amount of time, make sure not rod down to below 40% health, or you may get aggro and be subject to short brutal death.  When time is of the essence, heals are better than regeneration, except for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Torpor</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Again, because speed may be critical, it is better to pump out some pristine, three charge rods, then eat a rod or two by yourself, rather than take a charge off each rod before dropping it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (which is more sustainable)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
